{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20180925211425|861209016","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Ron_DeSantis","to":"Ron DeSantis"}],"pages":{"36729527":{"pageid":36729527,"ns":0,"title":"Ron DeSantis","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-09-25T21:47:50Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Ron DeSantis\n| image = Ron DeSantis, Official Portrait, 113th Congress.jpg\n| state = [[Florida]]\n| district = {{ushr|FL|6|6th}}\n| term_start = January 3, 2013\n| term_end = September 10, 2018\n| predecessor = [[Cliff Stearns]]\n| successor = ''Vacant''\n| birth_name = Ronald Dion DeSantis\n| birth_date = {{nowrap|{{birth date and age|1978|9|14}}}}\n| birth_place = [[Jacksonville, Florida]], [[U.S.]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Casey DeSantis|Casey Black]]|2010}}\n| children = 2\n| education = [[Yale University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Harvard University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n| website = \n| allegiance = {{flag|United States}}\n| branch = {{flag|United States Navy}}\n| serviceyears = 2004\u20132010 (Active)<br>2010\u2013present (Reserve)\n| rank = [[File:US-O4 insignia.svg|18px]] [[Lieutenant commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]]\n| unit = [[Judge Advocate General's Corps, U.S. Navy|Judge Advocate General's Corps]]\n| battles = [[Iraq War]]\n| mawards = [[Bronze Star Medal|Bronze Star]]<br>[[Iraq Campaign Medal]]\n}}\n'''Ronald Dion DeSantis''' (born September 14, 1978) is an American politician and a former [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|FL|6}}. After graduating from [[Yale University]] and [[Harvard Law School]], DeSantis served as an attorney and as a [[Judge Advocate General's Corps, U.S. Navy|JAG]] prosecutor in the Navy. A [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], he was first elected to the House of Representatives in 2012.\n\nDeSantis ran in [[United States Senate election in Florida, 2016|Florida's 2016 U.S. Senate election]], but ended his campaign when incumbent Senator [[Marco Rubio]] announced that he would seek re-election.<ref name=\"DeSantisRuns\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2016/06/22/marco-rubio-will-seek-senate-re-election-reversing-pledge-not-to-run|title=Marco Rubio will seek Senate reelection, reversing pledge not to run|publisher=The Washington Post|last1=DeBonis|first1=Mike|last2=O'Keefe|first2=Ed|last3=Sullivan|first3=Sean|date=June 22, 2016|accessdate=December 22, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"DeSantisRunsTwo\">{{cite web|url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/214270-whats-ron-desantis-next-move-stay-tuned|title=Reports: Ron DeSantis to run for re-election in CD 6|publisher=Florida Politics|last=Gancarski|first=A.G.|date=June 22, 2016|accessdate=December 22, 2017}}</ref> DeSantis then opted to run for re-election to his U.S. House seat and was re-elected in November 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kopan|first1=Tal|title=Another GOP challenger clears way for Marco Rubio|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/06/24/politics/marco-rubio-senate-todd-wilcox|accessdate=June 29, 2016|publisher=CNN|date=June 24, 2016}}</ref> Described as a \"top Trump ally\", DeSantis drew increased attention in 2017 for his frequent criticisms of [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u2013present)|Special Counsel Robert Mueller's investigation]] into Russian interference in the 2016 election.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/06/02/gowdy-trump-spygate-theory-617948|title=Trump allies gang up on Gowdy|last=|first=|date=|work=Politico|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en|quote=Rep. Ron DeSantis (R-Fla.), a top Trump ally seeking to undermine the ongoing Russia probes}}</ref> \n\nOn August 28, 2018, DeSantis won the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Primary election|primary]] for [[Florida gubernatorial election, 2018|Governor of Florida]]. On September 10, 2018, DeSantis resigned his seat in the House of Representatives to focus on his gubernatorial campaign.\n\n==Early life and education==\nRonald Dion DeSantis was born on September 14, 1978 in [[Jacksonville, Florida]], the son of Karen (Rogers) and Ronald DeSantis.<ref>https://obittree.com/obituary/us/florida/palm-harbor/curlew-hills-memory-gardens-inc/christina-desantis/2164525/</ref> In 1991 he was a member of the [[Little League]] team from Dunedin National that went on from the regular season to the [[Little League World Series]] in [[Williamsport, Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gonzales|first1=Nathan|title=Fall Elections Shape Future Rosters|url=http://www.rollcall.com/features/Baseball-Program_2012/baseball/Fall-Elections-Shape-Future-Rosters-215692-1.html|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Roll Call|date=June 26, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Vaccaro|first1=Ron|title=Baseball's DeSantis shines on Yale Field of dreams|url=http://yaledailynews.com/blog/2001/03/30/baseballs-desantis-shines-on-yale-field-of-dreams|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Yale News|date=March 30, 2001}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduating in 1997 from [[Dunedin High School]] in [[Dunedin, Florida]], DeSantis attended [[Yale University]], graduating with a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in history in 2001.  He then attended [[Harvard Law School]], receiving his [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/137630/ron-desantis|title=Ron DeSantis' Biography \u2013 The Voter's Self Defense System|publisher=Vote Smart|accessdate=February 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Military service==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=September 2018}}\n \nDeSantis received his [[United States Navy Reserve|Reserve Naval officer's commission]] and  assignment to Judge Advocate General's Corps (JAG) in 2004 at the U.S. Naval Reserve Center in [[Dallas]], Texas while still a student at Harvard Law School.  He completed [[Naval Justice School|U.S. Naval Justice School]] in 2005. Later that year, he received orders from Trial Service Office Command South East at the [[Naval Station Mayport]], Florida, as a [[military justice|JAG prosecutor]]. In 2006, he was promoted from [[Lieutenant Junior Grade]] (LTJG) to Lieutenant (LT). He worked for the [[Joint Task Force Guantanamo|Joint Task Force-Guantanamo Commander]] (JTF-GTMO), working directly with detainees at the [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp|Guantanamo Bay Joint Detention Facility]].<ref name=congress-bio>{{Cite web |url=https://desantis.house.gov/about | title=About | access-date=September 1, 2018}}</ref>{{Cn|date= September 2018}}<ref name=Mahoney-082918>{{Cite web |url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/state-politics/article217545910.html | title=Who is Ron DeSantis, the Republican running for Florida governor? |publisher=''[[Miami Herald]]''|last=Mahoney | first=Emily | date= August 29, 2018 | access-date=September 1, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Mahoney-081418>{{Cite web |url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/state-politics/article216615190.html | title=This candidate for Florida governor cites serving at Guant\u00e1namo. What did he do there? |publisher=''[[Miami Herald]]''|last=Mahoney | date= August 14, 2018 | first=Emily |access-date=September 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\t\nIn 2007, DeSantis reported to the [[Naval Special Warfare Command]] Group in [[Coronado, California]], where he was assigned to [[SEAL Team One]] and deployed to [[Iraq War of 2003|Iraq]]<ref name=farrington>{{cite news|last1=Farrington|first1=Brenda|title=Republican Congressman DeSantis to run for Rubio Senate seat|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-ap-senate-florida-desantis-20150505-story.html|accessdate=27 May 2016|agency=Associated Press|publisher=Sun Sentinel|date=May 5, 2015}}</ref> with the [[Iraq troop surge|troop surge]] as the Legal Advisor to the SEAL Commander, Special Operations Task Force-West in [[Fallujah]].<ref name=congress-bio /><ref name=Mahoney-082918 /><ref name=Mahoney-081418 />\n\t\nHe returned to the United States in April 2008, at which time he was reassigned to the Naval Region Southeast Legal Service. He was appointed by the [[U.S. Department of Justice]] to serve as a [[federal prosecutor]]<ref name=farrington /> at the [[U.S. Attorney for the Middle District of Florida|U.S. Attorney's Office in the Middle District of Florida]]. DeSantis was assigned as a Trial Defense Counsel until his honorable discharge from active duty in February 2010. He concurrently accepted a Reserve commission as a Lieutenant, Judge Advocate General Corps, in the [[US Navy Reserve]].<ref name=wsj /> He was awarded the [[Bronze Star Medal]] and the [[Iraq Campaign Medal]].<ref name=congress-bio /><ref name=Mahoney-082918 /><ref name=Mahoney-081418 />\n\n==Writing==\nHe authored a book entitled ''Dreams From Our Founding Fathers: First Principles in the Age of Obama'', which was published in 2011.<ref name=\"wsj\">{{cite news|title=Ron DeSantis (R)|url=http://projects.wsj.com/campaign2012/candidates/view/ron-desantis--FL-H|accessdate=27 May 2016|work=Election 2012|publisher=Wall Street Journal}}</ref> His writing has appeared in ''[[National Review]]'', ''[[The Washington Times]]'', ''[[The American Spectator]]'', ''[[Human Events]]'', and ''[[American Thinker]]''.<ref name=wsj/>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n===2012 election===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Florida, 2012#District 6}}\nIn 2012, DeSantis ran in the Republican primary for [[Florida's 6th congressional district]]. The district had previously been the 7th District, represented by 20-year Republican incumbent [[John Mica]]. However, most of Mica's territory in [[Orange County, Florida|Orange County]] had been drawn into the new 7th District\u2014the old 24th District. Mica opted to run in the reconfigured 7th, making the 6th an open seat.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nDeSantis won the six-candidate Republican primary with 39% of the vote, with the runner-up, State Representative [[Fred Costello]], obtaining 23%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=756561|title=FL District 06 \u2013 R Primary Race|date=August 14, 2012|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=February 12, 2016}}</ref> In the November general election, DeSantis defeated Democrat [[Heather Beaven]] by 57\u201343%, with majorities in all four counties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=736113|title=FL District 06 Race|date=November 6, 2012|publisher=Our Campaigns|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\nPrior to the [[114th United States Congress]], DeSantis was named the Chairman of the [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on National Security|Subcommittee on National Security]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin|title=Despite Opposing 'CRomnibus,' Sophomore Ron DeSantis Ascends Congressional Ladder|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/story/despite-opposing-cromnibus-sophomore-ron-desantis-ascends-congressional-ladder|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Sunshine State News|date=December 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]]'''\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Middle East and South Asia|Subcommittee on the Middle East and South Asia]]\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Western Hemisphere|Subcommittee on the Western Hemisphere]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on the Judiciary|Committee on the Judiciary]]'''\n** [[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on the Constitution and Civil Justice|Subcommittee on the Constitution and Civil Justice]]\n** [[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Courts, Intellectual Property and the Internet|Subcommittee on Courts, Intellectual Property and the Internet]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|Committee on Oversight and Government Reform]]'''\n** [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Federal Workforce, U.S. Postal Service and the Census|Subcommittee on Federal Workforce, U.S. Postal Service and the Census]]\n** [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Economic Growth, Job Creation and Regulatory Affairs|Subcommittee on Economic Growth, Job Creation and Regulatory Affairs]]\n* '''[[Republican Study Committee]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov|accessdate=November 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Legislation===\nOn January 29, 2014, DeSantis introduced into the House the [[Faithful Execution of the Law Act of 2014 (H.R. 3973; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would direct the [[United States Department of Justice]] to report to the [[United States Congress]] whenever any [[List of United States federal agencies|federal agency]] refrains from enforcing laws or regulations for any reason.<ref name=3973cbo>{{cite web|title=H.R. 3973 \u2013 CBO|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45177|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=March 11, 2014}}</ref><ref name=3972sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 3972 \u2013 Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/3973|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=March 11, 2014}}</ref> In the report, the government would have to explain why it had decided not to enforce that law.<ref name=HtargetsObamalawEnf>{{cite news|last=Kasperowicz|first=Pete|title=House targets Obama's law enforcement|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/government-oversight/200167-house-to-attack-obamas-non-enforcement-next-week|accessdate=March 12, 2014|newspaper=The Hill|date=March 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis spoke in favor of the bill, arguing that \"President Obama has not only failed to uphold several of our nation's laws, he has vowed to continue to do so in order to enact his unpopular agenda. ... The American people deserve to know exactly which laws the Obama administration is refusing to enforce and why.\"<ref name=\"HtargetsObamalawEnf\"/>\n\nIn 2013, DeSantis signed a pledge sponsored by [[Americans for Prosperity]] promising to vote against any global warming legislation that would raise taxes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://americansforprosperity.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/DeSantis_Ron.pdf|title=Americans for Prosperity Applauds U.S. Representative Ron DeSantis|accessdate=October 8, 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141015194819/http://americansforprosperity.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/DeSantis_Ron.pdf|archivedate=October 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn August 24, 2017, DeSantis added a [[rider (legislation)|rider]] to the proposed fiscal 2018 spending bill package that would end funding for the [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u2013present)|2017 Special Counsel investigation]] \"or for the investigation under that order of matters occurring before June 2015\" (the month Trump announced he was running for president) 180 days after passage of the bill.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/348343-gop-lawmaker-proposes-amendment-that-would-stop-funding-for-special-counsel|title=GOP lawmaker proposes amendment to stop Mueller investigation after 180 days|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|author=Shelbourne, Mallory|date=August 28, 2017|access-date=August 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe amendment would counter a bipartisan bill authored by two Democratic and two Republican U.S. Senators that was meant to limit the president's power to fire the special counsel. The DeSantis amendment would potentially cut off funding for the investigation by November 2017. It was also a response to Deputy Attorney General [[Rod Rosenstein]]'s statement that the [[United States Department of Justice|DOJ]], \"doesn't conduct [[fishing expedition]]s.\"<ref>[http://www.newsweek.com/one-amendment-could-stop-trump-russia-investigation-november-656525 One amendment could stop Russia investigation by November], ''[[Newsweek]]'', Greg Price, August 29, 2017; retrieved August 30, 2017.</ref> DeSantis stated that the May 17, 2017 DOJ order \"didn't identify a crime to be investigated and practically invites a fishing expedition.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/08/28/mueller-investigation-republicans-russia-242108|title=Republican floats measure to kill Mueller probe after 6 months|work=[[Politico]]|author=Wright, Austin|date=August 28, 2017|access-date=August 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe is a founding member of the [[Freedom Caucus]], a group of congressional conservatives.<ref name=Contorno-180810>{{cite web | url=https://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2018/08/10/ron-desantis-wants-to-lead-florida-through-hurricanes-he-voted-against-helping-sandy-victims/ | title=Ron DeSantis wants to lead Florida through hurricanes. He voted against helping Sandy victims. | work=[[Tampa Bay Times]] | date=August 10, 2018 | accessdate=September 11, 2018 | first=Steve | last=Contorno}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=What is the House Freedom Caucus, and who's in it?|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2015/10/20/house-freedom-caucus-what-is-it-and-whos-in-it|publisher=Pew Research Center|date=October 20, 2015|accessdate=October 26, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Mahoney-081418 />\n\n==2016 U.S. Senate candidacy==\n{{main|United States Senate election in Florida, 2016}}\nOn May 6, 2015, DeSantis announced that he was running for the [[United States Senate]] seat held by [[Marco Rubio]], who initially did not file to run for re-election due to [[Marco Rubio presidential campaign, 2016|his bid]] for the [[President of the United States|U.S. presidency]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stein|first1=Letitia|title=Florida Congressman Ron DeSantis running for U.S. Senate|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/05/06/us-usa-election-florida-senate-idUSKBN0NR1S420150506|accessdate=May 7, 2015|publisher=Reuters|date=May 6, 2015}}</ref> He was endorsed by the fiscally conservative [[Club for Growth]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Video: Club for Growth backs DeSantis|url=http://thehill.com/video/in-the-news/241205-video-club-for-growth-backs-desantis|accessdate=June 3, 2015|publisher=The Hill|date=May 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis withdrew from the race following incumbent Senator [[Marco Rubio]]'s announcement that he would seek reelection to the Senate, reversing his initial pledge not to run, on June 22, 2016.<ref name=\"DeSantisRuns\"/><ref name=\"DeSantisRunsTwo\"/> After dropping his U.S. Senate bid, DeSantis filed to run for re-election to his U.S. House seat.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n==2018 gubernatorial candidacy==\n{{main|Florida gubernatorial election, 2018}}\n{{Multiple issues|section=yes|\n{{Unbalanced|section|date=September 2018}}\n{{POV-section|date=September 2018}}\n}}\nIn January 2018, DeSantis announced his candidacy for [[Governor of Florida]] to succeed term-limited Republican incumbent [[Rick Scott]]. President [[Donald Trump]] stated in December 2017 that he would support DeSantis should he run for Governor.<ref>{{cite web|last=Farrington|first=Brendan|url=https://apnews.com/2bea559f0e1e4e1dbbaf79775ab35471|title=Trump's tweeted choice for Florida governor enters the race|work=[[Associated Press]] News|accessdate=January 5, 2018}}</ref> During the Republican primary, DeSantis emphasized his support for Trump by running an ad where DeSantis taught his children how to \"build the wall\" and say \"Make America Great Again\" and by dressing one of his children in a tiny red \"Make America Great Again\" jumper.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2018/07/30/new-lighthearted-ron-desantis-ad-features-his-family-trump-jokes/|title=New lighthearted Ron DeSantis ad features his family, Trump jokes|last=Mahoney|first=Emily|work=Tampa Bay Times|access-date=2018-07-30|language=en-US}}</ref> Asked if he could name an issue where he disagreed with Trump, DeSantis did not name a single issue.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/30/us/politics/florida-governor-election.html|title=In Florida, Not All Politics Are Local, as Trump Shapes Governor\u2019s Race|access-date=2018-07-30|language=en}}</ref> On July 30, 2018, Jonathan Martin of ''The New York Times'' wrote that the support DeSantis's primary campaign had received demonstrated both Trump's kingmaking capacity in a Republican-trending state but also a \"broader nationalization of conservative politics\" wherein \"a willingness to hurl rhetorical lightning bolts at the left, the media and special counsel Robert S. Mueller can override local credentials, local endorsements and preparedness for a state-based job.\"<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nOn August 28, 2018, DeSantis won the Republican primary. His [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] opponent in the [[Florida gubernatorial election, 2018|general election]] is [[Andrew Gillum]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/28/us/politics/florida-arizona-election-results.html|title=Andrew Gillum, a Black Progressive, and Ron DeSantis, a Trump Acolyte, Win Florida Governor Primaries|access-date=2018-08-29|language=en}}</ref> The race is \"widely seen as a toss-up.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/gop-florida-governor-nominee-ron-desantis-criticized-for-monkey-remark/|title=GOP Florida governor nominee Ron DeSantis criticized for \"monkey\" remark|work=CBS News|date=2018-08-29|access-date=2018-09-22|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis\u2019s gubernatorial platform includes support for legislation that would allow persons with concealed weapons permits to carry firearms openly.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/politics/political-pulse/os-governor-race-desantis-gillum-issues-20180831-story.html|title=Florida governor's race: Where Ron DeSantis, Andrew Gillum stand on the issues|work=Orlando Sentinel|last=Rohrer|first=Gray|date=2018-08-31|access-date=2018-09-22|language=en-US}}</ref> He also supports a law mandating the use of E-verify by businesses and a state-level ban on \"sanctuary-city\" protections for undocumented immigrants.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/politics/political-pulse/os-governor-race-desantis-gillum-issues-20180831-story.html|title=Florida governor's race: Where Ron DeSantis, Andrew Gillum stand on the issues|work=Orlando Sentinel|last=Rohrer|first=Gray|date=2018-08-31|access-date=2018-09-22|language=en-US}}</ref> DeSantis has promised to stop the spread of polluted water from Lake Okeechobee.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/politics/political-pulse/os-governor-race-desantis-gillum-issues-20180831-story.html|title=Florida governor's race: Where Ron DeSantis, Andrew Gillum stand on the issues|work=Orlando Sentinel|last=Rohrer|first=Gray|date=2018-08-31|access-date=2018-09-22|language=en-US}}</ref> DeSantis has also expressed support for a state constitutional amendment to require a supermajority vote for any tax increases.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/politics/fl-reg-gillum-desantis-issues-20180830-story.html|title=Where do governor hopefuls Ron DeSantis, Andrew Gillum stand on the issues?|work=Sun Sentinel|last=Swisher|first=Skyler|date=2018-08-31|access-date=2018-09-22|language=en-US}}</ref> He opposes allowing able-bodied, childless adults to receive Medicaid.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/politics/fl-reg-gillum-desantis-issues-20180830-story.html|title=Where do governor hopefuls Ron DeSantis, Andrew Gillum stand on the issues?|work=Sun Sentinel|last=Swisher|first=Skyler|date=2018-08-31|access-date=2018-09-22|language=en-US}}</ref> DeSantis has stated that he would implement a medical marijuana program, but opposes the legalization of recreational marijuana.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/politics/fl-reg-gillum-desantis-issues-20180830-story.html|title=Where do governor hopefuls Ron DeSantis, Andrew Gillum stand on the issues?|work=Sun Sentinel|last=Swisher|first=Skyler|date=2018-08-31|access-date=2018-09-22|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>http://floridapolitics.com/archives/267561-ron-desantis-gets-solid-hits-on-national-issues-in-fox-news-debate</ref><ref>http://news.wfsu.org/post/putnam-desantis-find-common-ground-opposing-recreational-pot</ref>\n\nOn August 29, 2018, DeSantis came under fire for comments that were allegedly racially charged. DeSantis said: \"The last thing we need to do is to monkey this up by trying to embrace a socialist agenda with huge tax increases and bankrupting the state. That is not going to work. That's not going to be good for Florida.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/politics-news/desantis-under-fire-saying-florida-should-t-monkey-electing-gillum-n904746|title=DeSantis under fire for saying Florida shouldn't 'monkey this up' by electing Gillum, who is black|work=NBC News|access-date=2018-08-29|language=en-US}}</ref> DeSantis was accused of using the word \"monkey\" as a [[Dog-whistle politics|racist dog whistle]]; his opponent, Gillum, is African-American.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/29/us/politics/desantis-monkey-up-gillum.html|title=DeSantis Warns Florida Not to \u2018Monkey This Up,\u2019 and Many Hear a Racist Dog Whistle|last=Jacobs|first=Julia|date=2018-08-29|website=New York Times|language=en-US|access-date=2018-08-29}}</ref> Amid the controversy over DeSantis' comments, ''[[the Washington Post]]'' and the ''[[Naples Daily News]]'' reported that DeSantis had on four occasions appeared at racially charged conferences at the [[David Horowitz Freedom Center]] that featured various right-wing provocateurs as speakers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/gop-candidate-for-fla-governor-spoke-at-racially-charged-events/2018/09/09/c6d3a63c-b114-11e8-a810-4d6b627c3d5d_story.html|title=GOP candidate for Fla. governor spoke at racially charged events|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2018-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://eu.naplesnews.com/story/news/politics/2018/06/22/ron-desantis-accepted-luxury-hotel-stay-attend-right-wing-event/723598002/|title=DeSantis attended convention with speakers who have suggested killing Muslims, demeaned women|work=Naples Daily News|access-date=2018-09-10|language=en}}</ref> DeSantis has stated that his comment had \"'zero to do with race.'\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/404355-desantis-monkey-comment-has-zero-to-do-with-race|title=DeSantis: 'Monkey' comment has 'zero to do with race'|work=TheHill.com|last=Axelrod|first=Tal|date=2018-08-30|access-date=2018-09-22}}</ref> \n\nIn September 2018, DeSantis announced state Rep. Jeanette Nunez as his running mate.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.jacksonville.com/news/20180906/andrew-gillum-ron-desantis-select-running-mates|title=Andrew Gillum, Ron DeSantis select running mates|last=Kennedy|first=John|work=Jacksonville.com|access-date=2018-09-106language=en-US}}</ref> He resigned his seat in the U.S. House of Representatives on September 10, 2018, to focus on his gubernatorial candidacy.<ref name=Moe-180910>{{cite web | url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/congress/rep-ron-desantis-resigns-congress-n908146 | title=Amid heated governor's race, Ron DeSantis resigns from Congress | work=[[NBC News]] | date=September 10, 2018 | accessdate=September 10, 2018 | first=Alex | last=Moe | first2=Rebecca | last2=Shabad | first3=Ali | last3=Vitali}}</ref> That same month, DeSantis was criticized for not having a fully-formed policy platform for his gubernatorial campaign.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2018/09/13/morning-joe-mocks-ron-desantis-for-ducking-tough-questions-on-florida-issues/|title=Morning Joe mocks Ron DeSantis for ducking tough questions on Florida issues|last=Contorno|first=Steve|work=Tampa Bay Times|access-date=2018-09-21|language=en-US}}</ref> He cancelled a planned interview with the ''Tampa Bay Times'' to have additional time to put together a platform before an in-depth policy interview.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n==Political positions==\n[[File:Representative Ron DeSantis, Iran's Missile Program (17983165814).jpg|thumbnail|right|DeSantis speaking at the Hudson Institute]]\nDeSantis is a staunch conservative.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/states/florida/story/2017/12/22/trump-endorses-desantis-for-governor-via-twitter-161236|title=Trump endorses DeSantis for governor via Twitter|work=Politico PRO|access-date=2017-12-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/itsallpolitics/2015/05/07/404805852/meet-the-tea-partys-new-favorite-candidate|title=Meet The Tea Party's New Favorite Candidate|work=NPR.org|access-date=2017-12-23|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/ron-desantis-tea-party-favorite-becomes-first-republican-to-enter-senate-race-7597712|title=Ron DeSantis, Tea Party Favorite, Becomes First Republican to Enter Senate Race|last=Munzenrieder|first=Kyle|date=2015-05-06|work=Miami New Times|access-date=2017-12-23}}</ref> DeSantis was endorsed by the socially conservative [[Family Research Council Action PAC]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://orlando-politics.com/2015/11/23/ron-desantis-endorsed-by-common-core-opponent-frc-action-pac|title=Ron DeSantis endorsed by Common Core opponent FRC Action PAC|last1=Torres|first1=Frank|date=November 23, 2015|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=The Orlando Political Observer|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125162156/http://orlando-politics.com/2015/11/23/ron-desantis-endorsed-by-common-core-opponent-frc-action-pac|archivedate=November 25, 2015|df=}}</ref>\n\n=== Cannabis/Marijuana ===\nDeSantis supports the implementation of a medical marijuana program in Florida, but opposes the legalization of recreational marijuana.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/politics/fl-reg-gillum-desantis-issues-20180830-story.html|title=Where do governor hopefuls Ron DeSantis, Andrew Gillum stand on the issues?|work=Sun Sentinel|last=Swisher|first=Skyler|date=2018-08-31|access-date=2018-09-22|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>http://floridapolitics.com/archives/267561-ron-desantis-gets-solid-hits-on-national-issues-in-fox-news-debate</ref><ref>http://news.wfsu.org/post/putnam-desantis-find-common-ground-opposing-recreational-pot</ref><ref>https://www.gainesville.com/news/20180601/legalizing-cannabis-divides-candidates-for-governor</ref> He voted against the Veterans Equal Access Amendment that would give veterans access to medical marijuana if recommended by their [[Veterans Health Administration]] doctor and if it is legal for medicinal purposes in their state of residence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.safeaccessnow.org/veteran_2017_blumenauer|title=2016 Congressional Scorecard|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n=== Contraceptives and abortion ===\n\nDeSantis [[Opposition to abortion|opposes abortion]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/424801/planned-parenthood-chief-abortion-survivor-baby-entitled-medical-care-joel-gehrke|title=Planned Parenthood Head: An Abortion Survivor is a 'Baby' Entitled to Medical Care|last1=Gehkre|first1=Joel|date=September 29, 2015|accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=National Review}}</ref> and has denounced [[Planned Parenthood]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/186587-ron-desantis-denounces-planned-parenthoods-loathsome-practice|title=Ron DeSantis denounces Planned Parenthood's alleged \"loathsome practice\"|last1=Gancarski|first1=A.G.|date=July 15, 2015|accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=Florida Politics}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis agreed with the U.S. Supreme Court's decision in ''[[Burwell v. Hobby Lobby Stores, Inc.]]'', saying \"This case does not concern the availability or legality of contraceptives, and individuals can obtain and use these as they see fit. The question is simply whether the government can force the owners of Hobby Lobby to pay for abortifacients in violation of their faith.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/story/florida-congressmen-divide-over-hobby-lobby-case|title=Florida Congressmen Divide Over Hobby Lobby Case|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin|date=March 26, 2014|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=Sunshine State News}}</ref>\n\n=== Economy ===\nDeSantis has said that the debate in Washington, D.C. over how to reduce the deficit should shift emphasis from tax increases to curtailing spending and triggering economic growth.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jordan|first1=Douglas|title=DeSantis emphasizes importance of economic growth|url=http://staugustine.com/news/local-news/2012-12-15/desantis-economic-growth-essential#.VtN1cPHvOad|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=St. Augustine Record|date=December 16, 2012}}</ref> He supports a \"no budget no pay\" policy for Congress to encourage the passage of a budget.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wexler|first1=Gene|title=New St. Johns Rep. opens up on financial and governmental reforms|url=http://www.wokv.com/news/news/local/new-st-johns-rep-opens-financial-and-governmental-/nTmcb|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=WOKV|date=January 3, 2013}}</ref> He believes the [[Federal Reserve System]] should be audited.<ref name=roll/>\n\nIn the wake of the alleged [[IRS targeting controversy]], DeSantis called for the resignation of Internal Revenue Service Commissioner [[John Koskinen]] for having \"failed the American people by frustrating Congress's attempts to ascertain the truth.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=DeSantis|first1=Ron|last2=Jordan|first2=Jim|title=The Stonewall at the Top of the IRS|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-stonewall-at-the-top-of-the-irs-1438039060|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=July 27, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Perry|first1=Mitch|title=Ron DeSantis wants Obama to remove IRS commissioner\u2014or else|url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/187207-ron-desantis-wants-obama-to-remove-irs-commissioner-or-else|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=Florida Politics|date=July 28, 2015}}</ref> He co-sponsored a bill to impeach Koskinen for violating the public's trust.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://oversight.house.gov/release/resolution-introduced-impeach-irs-commissioner|title=Resolution Introduced to Impeach IRS Commissioner|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=House Oversight Committee|date=October 27, 2015}}</ref> In 2015, DeSantis was named \"Taxpayer Superhero\" by [[Citizens Against Government Waste]], a conservative think-tank.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gancarski|first1=July 31, 2015|title=Email insights: Ron DeSantis, \"Taxpayer Superhero\"|url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/187434-email-insights-ron-desantis-taxpayer-superhero|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=Florida Politics|date=July 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis supported the [[Regulations from the Executive in Need of Scrutiny Act|Regulations from the Executive in Need of Scrutiny (REINS) Act]], which would require that regulations that have a significant economic impact be subject to a vote of Congress prior to taking effect.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Siefring|first1=Neil|title=The REINS Act will keep regulations and their costs in check|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/pundits-blog/economy-budget/250178-the-reins-act-will-keep-regulations-and-their-costs-in|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=The Hill|date=August 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis introduced the [[Let Seniors Work Act]], which would repeal the [[Earnings test (US)|Retirement Earnings Test]] and exempt senior citizens from the 12.4% [[Federal Insurance Contributions Act tax|Social Security payroll tax]], and he co-sponsored a measure to eliminate taxes on [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] benefits.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin|title=Marco Rubio, Ron DeSantis Restore 'Let Seniors Work Act'|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/story/marco-rubio-ron-desantis-restore-let-seniors-work-act|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=Sunshine State News|date=March 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis sponsored the Transportation Empowerment Act, which would transfer much of the responsibility for transportation projects to the individual states and sharply reduce the [[federal gas tax]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Laing|first1=Keith|title=Bill filed to sharply reduce the gas tax|url=http://thehill.com/policy/transportation/244597-bill-filed-to-eliminate-the-gas-tax|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=The Hill|date=June 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Lee|first1=Mike|last2=DeSantis|first2=Ron|title=Economy Commentary Let America Fix the Highways Washington Broke|url=http://dailysignal.com/2015/06/10/let-america-fix-the-highways-washington-broke|accessdate=February 28, 2016|publisher=The Daily Signal|date=June 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis has opposed legislation to require online retailers to collect and pay state sales tax.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dixon|first1=Matt|title=Retail group assails DeSantis over Internet sales tax|url=http://staugustine.com/news/local-news/2013-06-27#.VtONM_HvOac|accessdate=February 29, 2016|publisher=St. Augustine Record|date=June 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe voted in favor of the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]].<ref name=\"Almukhtar122017\">{{cite news|last1=Almukhtar|first1=Sarah|title=How Each House Member Voted on the Tax Bill|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/12/19/us/politics/tax-bill-house-live-vote.html?_r=0|website=The New York Times|accessdate=22 December 2017|date=19 December 2017}}</ref> DeSantis says the bill will bring a \"dramatically lower tax rate\" and \"full expensing of capital investments.\" DeSantis also believes the act will bring more jobs to America.<ref name=\"Brown121917\">{{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=Stephanie|title=Northeast Florida lawmakers divided on impact of tax reform plan   |website=www.wokv.com|url=http://www.wokv.com/news/local/northeast-florida-lawmakers-divided-impact-gop-tax-reform-plan/vyBF5BQ8kPldHOvKT0JGdK/|publisher=WOKV Radio|accessdate=22 December 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nDeSantis opposes federal education programs such as [[No Child Left Behind Act]] and [[Race to the Top]], saying that education policy should be made at the local level.<ref name=roll>{{cite news|title=Ron DeSantis, R-Fla. (6th District)|url=http://www.rollcall.com/new-members/ron-desantis-house-r-fla-6.html|accessdate=28 February 2016|publisher=Roll Call}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, DeSantis introduced the [[Higher Education Reform and Opportunity Act]], which would allow states to create their own accreditation systems. In an op-ed for the ''[[National Review]]'', DeSantis said that his legislation would give students \"access to federal loan money to put towards non-traditional educational opportunities, such as online learning courses, vocational schools, and apprenticeships in skilled trades.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=DeSantis|first1=Ron|last2=Lee|first2=Mike|title=Break Up the Higher-Ed Cartel|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/414848/break-higher-ed-cartel-ron-desantis-mike-lee|accessdate=February 29, 2016|publisher=National Review|date=March 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign relations===\n====Cuba====\nIn 2015, DeSantis introduced the Guantanamo Bay Recidivism Prevention Act, which would cut off foreign aid to countries that receive detainees if they show back up on the terrorism recidivism list.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin|title=Ron DeSantis: Releasing Guantanamo Detainees is a Security Threat|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/blog/ron-desanits-releasing-guantanamo-detainees-security-threat|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Sunshine State News|date=January 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis opposed President Obama's plan to shut down the [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp]], saying \"Bringing hardened terrorists to the U.S. homeland harms our national security.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin|title=Obama's GITMO Proposal Draws Fire From GOP Candidates Vying to Replace Marco Rubio|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/story/obamas-gitmo-propsoal-draws-fire-gop-candidates-vying-replace-marco-rubio|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Sunshine State News|date=February 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nRegarding the formal restart of diplomatic relations between the U.S. and Cuba, DeSantis said \"Raising the Cuban flag in the United States is a slap in the face to those who have experienced the brutality of the Castro regime.\"<ref name=reaction>{{cite news|last1=Leary|first1=Alex|title=Florida reaction to Cuba news|url=http://www.tampabay.com/blogs/the-buzz-florida-politics/florida-reaction-to-cuba-news/2237995|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Tampa Bay Times|date=July 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Iran====\nDeSantis opposed the [[Iran nuclear deal framework]], calling it \"a bad deal that will significantly degrade our national security.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cotton|first1=Tom|last2=DeSantis|first2=Ron|title=Congress Must Reject the Iran Deal|url=http://time.com/3978510/congress-must-reject-the-iran-deal|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Time|date=July 30, 2015}}</ref> DeSantis said \"the Iran deal gives Ayatollah Khamenei exactly what he wants: billions of dollars in sanctions relief, validation of the Iranian nuclear program, and the ability to stymie inspections.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=DeSantis Condemns Deal as a Gift to Iran's Ayatollah|url=https://desantis.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/desantis-condemns-deal-as-a-gift-to-irans-ayatollah|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Congressman Ron DeSantis|date=July 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring a line of questioning, DeSantis told Secretary of State [[John Kerry]] that the executive branch had a legal obligation to provide Congress with the details behind any side deals made between world leaders and Iran.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Torres|first1=Frank|title=DeSantis and Kerry get contentious over Iran Deal|url=http://orlando-politics.com/2015/07/29/desantis-and-kerry-get-contentious-over-iran-deal|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Orlando Political Observer|date=July 29, 2015}}</ref> DeSantis accused President Barack Obama of giving better treatment of Cuba's [[Raul Castro]] and Iran's Ayatollah [[Ali Khamenei]] than of Israel's [[Benjamin Netanyahu]].<ref name=save>{{cite news|last1=Man|first1=Anthony|title='We need to save the country', conservative U.S. Senate candidate tells Broward activists|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-ron-desantis-conservative-candidate-20150824-story.html|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Sun Sentinel|date=August 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Israel====\nIn 2013, DeSantis introduced the Palestinian Accountability Act, which would halt U.S. aid to the [[Palestinian National Authority|Palestinian Authority]] until it formally recognizes [[Israel]]'s right to exist as a Jewish state and cuts off all ties with the terror group [[Hamas]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kredo|first1=Adam|title=House Bill Would Cut Aid to Palestinian Authority|url=http://freebeacon.com/national-security/house-bill-would-cut-aid-to-palestinian-authority|accessdate=February 26, 2016|work=Washington Free Beacon|date=March 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, DeSantis co-introduced the Non-Discrimination of Israel in Labeling Act, which will defend the right of Israeli producers to label products manufactured in the West Bank as \"Israel\", \"Made in Israel\", or \"Product of Israel\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ganckarski|first1=A.G.|title=Ron DeSantis co-introduces non-discrimination of Israel in labeling act |url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/201890-ron-desantis-co-introduces-non-discrimination-of-israel-in-labeling-act|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Florida Politics|date=February 16, 2016}}</ref> DeSantis supported the move of the U.S. Embassy from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2018/05/13/scott-desantis-in-israel-for-u-s-embassy-opening/ |title=Scott, DeSantis in Israel for U.S. Embassy opening |publisher=Tampa Bay Times |date=2018-05-13 |accessdate=2018-08-29}}</ref>\n\n===Government===\nDeSantis opted not to receive his [[congressional pension]], and he filed a measure that would eliminate pensions for members of Congress.<ref name=roll/> After introducing the End Pensions in Congress Act, DeSantis said \"The Founding Fathers envisioned elected officials as part of a servant class, yet Washington has evolved into a ruling class culture.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Harper|first1=Jennifer|title=No more 'ruling class culture': New legislation would jettison pensions for Congress|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2015/feb/2/no-more-ruling-class-culture-new-legislaiton-would/|accessdate=28 February 2016|publisher=Washington Times|date=February 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis supports a constitutional amendment to impose [[term limit]]s for members of Congress, so that Representatives would be limited to three terms and senators to two terms.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Farrington|first1=Brendan|title=Republican Congressman DeSantis to run for Rubio Senate seat|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-ap-senate-florida-desantis-20150505-story.html|accessdate=February 28, 2016|agency=Associated Press|publisher=Sun Sentinel|date=May 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Gun law===\nDeSantis opposes [[gun control]]. He received an A+ rating from the [[National Rifle Association]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Keller|first1=Michael|title=This is Your Representative on Guns|url=http://thedailybeast.thisisyourreponguns.com/#Pane=overview&Chamber=House|accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=The Daily Beast|date=February 11, 2013}}</ref>\nHe is generally opposed to firearm regulation, saying, \"Very rarely do firearms restrictions affect criminals. They really only affect law-abiding citizens.\"<ref name=\"Maddock 2013\">{{cite news| title=Ron DeSantis Put On Spot By Sandy Hook Parents At Florida Town Hall| url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/02/20/ron-desantis-sandy-hook_n_2726089.html| last=Maddock| first=Preston| date=20 February 2013| work=HuffPost| access-date=23 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the 2018 [[Stoneman Douglas High School shooting]] in [[Parkland, Florida]], DeSantis expressed his support for hiring retired [[law enforcement officer]]s and military [[veteran]]s as armed guards for schools.<ref name=\"Bennett 2018\">{{cite news |last=Bennett |first=George |date=20 February 2018 |title=Ron DeSantis: Enlist retired military, cops to prevent school shootings |url=http://postonpolitics.blog.palmbeachpost.com/2018/02/20/ron-desantis-enlist-retired-military-cops-to-prevent-school-shootings/ |work=PalmBeachPost.com |location=Palm Beach, Florida |access-date=23 February 2018 }}</ref> He disagrees with legislation signed into law by Florida Governor Rick Scott that banned bump stocks, added a mandatory three-day waiting period for gun purchases, and raised the legal age for purchases from 18 to 21.<ref name=Mahoney-082118 /> He has expressed support for measures to improve federal background checks for purchasing firearms and has said that there is a need to intervene with those who are exhibiting warning signs of committing violence instead of waiting until a crime has been committed.<ref name=\"Bennett 2018\"/>\n\n===Healthcare===\nDeSantis is opposed to the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]].<ref name=\"Repeal\">{{cite press release|title=Rep. DeSantis Statement on ObamaCare Repeal|url=https://desantis.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/rep-desantis-statement-on-obamacare-repeal|publisher=Office of Congressman Ron DeSantis|date=May 16, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Moorhead|first1=Molly|title=Florida Rep. Ron DeSantis says 'Obamacare' tax is cheaper than insurance|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2013/jan/24/ron-desantis/desantis-says-obamacare-tax-cheaper-insurance/|accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=PolitiFact|date=January 24, 2013}}</ref> He has called for the \"full and complete repeal\" of the act.<ref name=\"Repeal\"/>\n\nIn March 2017, DeSantis said that he wasn't ready to support the [[American Health Care Act]], the House Republican effort to replace the Affordable Care Act.<ref>{{cite web|author=Tony Perry|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/gops-darrell-issa-represents-a-clear-test-for-anti-trump-democrats-trying-for-electoral-gains-in-2018/2017/03/11/5d20b0f0-05ed-11e7-ad5b-d22680e18d10_story.html|title=GOP\u2019s Darrell Issa represents a clear test for anti-Trump Democrats trying for electoral gains in 2018|website=Washington Post|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Immigration ===\nDeSantis was a critic of President Obama's immigration policies; he opposed Obama's deferred action programs ([[Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals]] (DACA) and [[Deferred Action for Parents of Americans]] (DAPA)) and accused him of failing to enforce immigration laws.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/story/ron-desantis-turns-heat-obama-failing-enforce-immigration-laws|title=Ron DeSantis Turns Up the Heat on Obama for Failing to Enforce Immigration Laws|last1=Derby|first1=Kevin|date=February 24, 2015|accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=Sunshine State News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://dailysignal.com/2015/06/17/before-skeptical-lawmakers-officials-defend-legality-of-obamas-immigration-actions|title=Before Skeptical Lawmakers, Officials Defend 'Legality' of Obama's Immigration Actions|last1=Scanlon|first1=Kate|date=June 17, 2015|accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=The Daily Signal}}</ref> DeSantis opposes \"sanctuary cities.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://video.foxbusiness.com/v/4358373421001/sanctuary-cities-under-fire-/?#sp=show-clips|title=\u2190 Shrink player Sanctuary cities under fire|date=July 16, 2015|accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=Fox News}}</ref> He is a co-sponsor of the Establishing Mandatory Minimums for Illegal Reentry Act of 2015, also known as Kate's Law, which would amend the Immigration and Nationality Act to increase penalties applicable to aliens who unlawfully reenter the United States after being removed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://trackbill.com/bill/us-hr3011-kates-law/1198394|title=HR3011 Kate's Law|publisher=TrackBill|accessdate=February 27, 2016}}</ref> In 2017, Desantis spoke at [[ACT! for America]], an anti-Muslim advocacy group.<ref name=-180917>{{cite web | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/elections/2018/09/17/ron-desantis-act-america-address/1333447002/ | title=Florida's Ron DeSantis spoke to group whose founder says devout Muslims can't be loyal Americans | work=[[USA Today]] | date=September 17, 2018 | accessdate=September 17, 2018 | first=Trevor | last=Aaronson}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[November 2015 Paris attacks]], DeSantis \"called for urgent recognition that Islamic extremism is to blame for the Paris attacks and should be seen as an enemy for America.\" DeSantis has said \"The enemy is an ideology rooted in militant Islam\" and has said that [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIS]] must be stopped and its members kept away from America.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/os-sunshine-summit-senate-candidates-20151114-story.html|title=GOP Senate candidates call for fight against Islamic militants after Paris attacks|last1=Powers|first1=Scott|date=November 14, 2015|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Orlando Sentinel}}</ref> Regarding U.S. policy toward refugees, DeSantis said \"the prudent policy is to err on the side of protecting the American people\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/transcript/2015/11/27/rep-ron-desantis-on-refugee-debate-err-on-side-protecting-american-people/|title=Rep. Ron DeSantis on refugee debate: 'Err on side of protecting the American people'|date=November 27, 2015|accessdate=February 26, 2016|publisher=Fox News}}</ref>\n\n=== LGBT rights ===\nDeSantis has a \"0\" rating from the [[Human Rights Campaign]] based on his record of voting on [[LGBT rights|LGBT]]-related issues and legislation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2016/10/07/rubios-score-plummets-to-0-in-hrc-congressional-ratings|title=Rubio's score plummets to '0' in HRC congressional ratings|last1=Johnson|first1=Chris|date=October 7, 2016|website=Washington Blade|accessdate=December 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Russia investigation===\nAccording to the ''[[Tampa Bay Times]]'', DeSantis \"made a name for himself&nbsp;[in&nbsp;2017] attacking special counsel Robert Mueller's investigation&nbsp;into Russian meddling in the 2016 election.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2018/01/05/rep-ron-desantis-declares-run-for-florida-governor/|title=Rep. Ron DeSantis declares run for Florida governor|last=Mower|first=Lawrence|work=Tampa Bay Times|access-date=2018-01-08|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nDeSantis proposed an amendment that would halt funding for Mueller's [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u2013present)|2017 Special Counsel investigation]] probe six months after the amendment's passage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://amendments-rules.house.gov/amendments/DESANT_055_xml824171651535153.pdf|title=Amendment to Division C of the Rules Committee Print 115-31 Offered by Mr. DeSantis of Florida|website=Amendments-rules.house.gov|format=PDF|accessdate=18 January 2018}}</ref> In addition, this provision would prohibit Mueller from investigating matters that occurred before June 2015, when Trump launched his presidential campaign.<ref>Austin Wright, [http://www.politico.com/story/2017/08/28/mueller-investigation-republicans-russia-242108 Republican floats measure to kill Mueller probe after 6 months], Politico.com, August 28, 2017.</ref> In December 2017, DeSantis asserted that if there was any evidence of collusion between members of the Trump campaign and Russian officials, it would already have been leaked.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/366923-judiciary-republican-if-there-was-any-trump-russia-collusion-it-would-have|title=Judiciary Republican: If there was any Trump-Russia collusion, it would have leaked months ago|last=Manchester|first=Julia|date=2017-12-31|work=TheHill|access-date=2018-01-08}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, while on the House Intelligence Committee, DeSantis voted on party lines to release a classified memo authored by Republicans on the committee which purported to show that the FBI abused its surveillance powers in the Russia investigation.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/justice-department/house-vote-releasing-classified-nunes-memo-about-fbi-eavesdropping-n842311|title=House intelligence panel votes to release classified Nunes memo about FBI eavesdropping|work=NBC News|access-date=2018-01-30|language=en}}</ref> DeSantis voted not to release a memo authored by Democrats on the committee which accused the Republicans on the committee of playing politics with national security.<ref name=\":0\" /> Democrats described the Republican-authored memo as grossly distorted and intended to discredit the Mueller Special Counsel investigation, and said that the Republicans on the committee had begun an investigation into the FBI and DOJ.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn April 2018, DeSantis called on FBI Director Christopher Wray to criminally investigate a number of officials involved in investigating Russian interference in the 2016 election, including former FBI Director James Comey, former Acting Director of the FBI Andrew McCabe, FBI Agent Peter Strzok and FBI Counsel Lisa Page.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/384312-trump-to-lawmakers-pressing-sessions-on-comey-good-luck-with-that|title=Trump to lawmakers pressing Sessions to investigate Comey and Clinton: 'Good luck with that'|last=Shelbourne|first=Mallory|date=2018-04-22|work=TheHill|access-date=2018-04-24|language=en}}</ref> DeSantis also called for investigations of a number of former Obama officials, including Loretta Lynch and Hillary Clinton.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/18/trump-allies-clinton-comey-lynch-criminal-investigations-532516|title=trump-allies-clinton-comey-lynch-criminal-investigations|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Veterans===\nDeSantis has sharply criticized the [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs]] for the [[Veterans Health Administration scandal of 2014]], in which veteran deaths were linked to fatal wait times. He co-sponsored the VA Accountability Act, which aims to increase accountability by providing for the removal or demotion of employees of the Department of Veterans Affairs based on performance or misconduct.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Winslow|first1=Hailey|title=Congressman Ron DeSantis pushes legislation to hold Veterans Affairs accountable|url=http://www.news4jax.com/news/florida/st-johns-county/congressman-ron-desantis-pushes-legislation-to-hold-veterans-affairs-accountable|accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=News 4 Jax|date=May 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Davis|first1=Clifford|title=Rep. Ron DeSantis pushes for VA reform in St. Augustine|url=http://jacksonville.com/news/politics/2014-05-05/story/rep-ron-desantis-pushes-va-reform-st-augustine|accessdate=February 27, 2016|publisher=Florida Times Union|date=May 5, 2014}}</ref> He is a member of the Post-9/11 Veterans Caucus.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Porter|first1=Thomas|title=IAVA Team Continues to Seek Path Forward for 9/11 First Responders|url=http://iava.org/blogs/iava-team-continues-to-seek-path-forward-for-911-first-responders-press-conference-tomorrow|publisher=Iraq & Afghanistan Veterans of America|accessdate=February 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Voting rights ===\n{{As of|August 2018}}, DeSantis had not taken a position on a November 2018 ballot initiative on the restoration of voting rights for felons.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2018/01/30/where-they-stand-candidates-for-governor-on-vote-for-felons/|title=Where they stand: Candidates for governor on vote for felons|last=Bousquet|first=Steve|work=Tampa Bay Times|access-date=2018-03-20|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=Pantazi-180824>{{cite web | url=http://www.jacksonville.com/news/20180817/floridas-prisons-are-more-expensive-than-ever-what-will-next-governor-do-about-it | title=Florida\u2019s prisons are more expensive than ever. What will the next governor do about it? | work=[[Florida Times-Union]] | date=August 24, 2018 | accessdate=August 17, 2018 | first=Andrew | last=Pantazi}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2010, DeSantis, who is a Roman Catholic<ref>{{cite web|url=http://media.cq.com/members/46138|title=RollCall.com \u2013 Member Profile \u2013 Rep. Ron DeSantis, R-Fla.|website=media.cq.com}}</ref> of Italian descent, married [[Casey DeSantis]]. DeSantis and his wife bought a home in [[Palm Coast, Florida|Palm Coast]] in July, 2016 after redistricting moved their home in Ponte Vedra Beach into the 4th congressional district.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mark Harper |url=http://www.news-journalonline.com/news/20160729/congressman-ron-desantis-moves-to-flagler-county|title=Congressman Ron DeSantis moves to Flagler County|website=News-journalonline.com|date=2016-09-30|accessdate=2016-10-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://floridaresidentdb.com/person/107083209/ronald_dion_desantis|title=Ronald Dion DeSantis \u2013 Florida Resident Database|date=October 19, 2016|accessdate=May 6, 2017|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019033354/https://floridaresidentdb.com/person/107083209/ronald_dion_desantis|archivedate=October 19, 2016|df=}}</ref> DeSantis and his wife have a daughter, Madison,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://desantis.house.gov/about|title=About \u2013 Congressman Ron DeSantis|website=desantis.house.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-03-27}}</ref> and a son, Mason.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{commonscat}}\n* [https://rondesantis.com// Campaign website]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Florida/Government/Federal/US_House/Ron_DeSantis_%5BR-06%5D}}\n* {{C-SPAN|rondesantis}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=D000621 | votesmart=137630 | fec=H2FL00292 | congress=ron-desantis/D000621 }}<!--\nLinks formerly displayed via the CongLinks template:\n* [http://ballotpedia.org/Ron_DeSantis Biography] at [[Ballotpedia]]\n* [http://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/412526 Congressional profile] at [[GovTrack]]\n* [http://www.opencongress.org/people/show/412526 Congressional profile] at [[Participatory Politics Foundation|OpenCongress]]\n* [http://www.rollcall.com/members/46138.html Congressional profile] at ''[[Roll Call]]''\n* [http://www.politifact.com/personalities/ron-desantis Fact-checking] at [[PolitiFact.com]]\n* [http://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/summary.php?cid=N00034746 Financial information (federal office)] at [[Center for Responsive Politics|OpenSecrets.org]]\n* [http://www.ontheissues.org/FL/Ron_DeSantis.htm Issue positions and quotes] at [[On the Issues]]\n* [http://www.c-spanvideo.org/rondesantis Appearances] on [[C-SPAN]] programs\n* [http://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/9f576f4a-4bbb-11e2-8758-b64a2997a921_topic.html Collected news and commentary] at ''[[The Washington Post]]'' -->\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Cliff Stearns]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[L